36	1	Design systems are essential for creating consistency and alignment across a product's user experience. I believe they serve as a framework that not only guides design decisions but also fosters collaboration among cross-functional teams. The key is to develop design principles that resonate with everyone involved; this means starting with a listening tour to understand the team's current challenges and aspirations, which can then inform the principles we create together. By doing this, we can ensure that the design system becomes a living document that everyone actively engages with and uses in their daily work.	answer	\N	{"user_feedback": {"rating": "thumbs_up", "user_id": 1, "submitted_at": "2025-09-07T22:16:01Z"}, "knowledge_base_influence": {"sources": [{"id": "chunk_115", "tags": "#productdesign, #principles, #process, #leadership, #ux", "title": "Creating Design Principles That Get Used (Part 1)", "category": "Blog Post", "confidence": "90.0", "is_framework": false, "word_matches": ["think", "design"], "content_snippet": "- Scale design thinking cross-functionally → Make design values accessible to PMs, engineers, and others, not just designers", "relevance_score": 70.0}, {"id": "chunk_116", "tags": "#productdesign, #principles, #process, #leadership, #ux", "title": "Creating Design Principles That Get Used (Part 2)", "category": "Blog Post", "confidence": "90.0", "is_framework": false, "word_matches": ["about", "design"], "content_snippet": "Before any words go on the page, I’ve found it essential to run a listening tour—surveying designers, PMs, engineers, and researchers about what feels inconsistent in the work", "relevance_score": 70.0}, {"id": "chunk_119", "tags": "#productdesign, #principles, #process, #leadership, #ux", "title": "Creating Design Principles That Get Used (Part 5)", "category": "Blog Post", "confidence": "90.0", "is_framework": false, "word_matches": ["design"], "content_snippet": "If I could go back, I’d have paired the staff desi