18	The Value Based Product Designer	This week on Draft\r\n\r\nLast week’s Revise Weekly lesson was about repeat sales from past customers. This week’s is about a related aspect: referrals from past customers to existing ones.\r\nThis fortnight’s Draft Analysis will be about shaving darlings Harry’s. I am a secret shaving snob, so this will be fun.\r\nThe Problem With Images\r\nIn a recent letter, I chatted about the ideal format for a case study, using Draft’s most recent one as an example. A few noted that I had a screenshot there – but given its size & crop ratio, along with the lack of a link back to the page in question, it wasn’t really helpful as a visual.\r\n\r\nThat is by design. If you’re a designer who focuses primarily on business value, then you should not have visuals in your portfolio, no matter how visually-oriented of a designer you may be.\r\n\r\nI know this is easy to say as a designer who focuses on text, layout, and behavior. Yet with visual portfolios, it is even more essential to omit visuals from any public expression of your work.\r\n\r\nThe constraint: economic buyers can’t read the meaning of images\r\n\r\nWhen we start out as designers, we’re so conversant in visual language that we’re utterly shocked when clients and stakeholders can’t understand our underlying thinking.\r\n\r\nYet over time, we come to understand that they’re coming to the engagement with their own motives, and we need to express our thinking in advance of sharing new work. Most of one’s growth as a designer comes in the form of strategic communication skills: pitching new work, justifying various decisions, and crafting a game plan of potential tradeoffs that may occur during a critique session.\r\n\r\nAs a result, when a value-based designer is about to engage in critique, they spend considerable time and energy setting up their thinking before sharing images. That keeps the conversation focused on the right goals, and allows us to justify strategic direction without regressing to a discussion of personal preferences or arbitrary, self-constructed goals.\r\n\r\nThink about a situation in your career where mockups were shared prematurely, or without annotation. It’s nearly certain that the client misinterpreted the work, leading to way more backpedaling and damage control than would be appropriate in any engagement. This isn’t good or bad; it’s a natural consequence of all humans being visual thinkers, and we need to view it as a necessary constraint of our profession, no matter if we’re purely visual (illustrators, etc), functional (interaction design, strategy), or somewhere in between.\r\n\r\nThe consequences\r\n\r\nThe tendency of economic buyers – no, humans – to downplay a designer’s thinking in favor of visuals has three key consequences. Any one of these should be enough to justify never using visuals in your portfolio again.\r\n\r\nConsequence 1: Visual portfolios don’t build consensus\r\n\r\nThe goal of a portfolio is to convey your thinking and focus. Good portfolios get a prospective client to come around to your point of view. As a result, they provide an opportunity for you to demonstrate your focus on the economic value that design can provide for their business.\r\n\r\nThe constraint here is that you are communicating, mostly, to strangers. You lack the luxury of an existing client relationship, and you’re probably passively selling your work to a growing audience on your website. What about a visual in and of itself is capable of this, in the face of the headwinds your design practice already faces?\r\n\r\nConsequence 2: Visual portfolios distract from your thinking\r\n\r\nVisuals are useful for conveying your overall style, which is unfortunately of no business importance to the reader.\r\n\r\nValue-based designers know work begets work. This is great for building up a reputation over time, especially within a specific positioning – but it also means that if prospective clients see any visuals, they will hire you in order to stamp out a clone of a past project – not to provide business value.\r\n\r\nConsequence 3: Visuals fundamentally can’t bolster a business argument\r\n\r\nYou are there to convey two things to the reader:\r\n\r\nDesign has business value. It’s 2017 and nobody knows this. I know. It’s dumb. You still have to undo all the damage that designer-artists have done – and continue to do – to the integrity of our profession over the past 30 years.\r\nYou use design as a tool to create business results. This should be self-explanatory. It proves you’re a safe bet. It shows you will provide a more reliable return on the company’s investment.\r\nIf someone sees a visual, they’re going to focus on the visual. And if they focus on the visual, they’re not going to fully understand the challenge, thinking, operational issues, and ultimately value-based upside that you’re capable of providing to a client.\r\n\r\nPretty’s cheap; strategy has real value\r\n\r\nEvery time you add a visual, you are downplaying the importance of any other text you’ve written. And there is nothing more important than the text. Nothing.\r\n\r\nThat’s why designers should use at least 1,000 words of explanation, justification, and business strategy per mockup shared to the client. Fortunately, in your portfolio, you can explain yourself however you want – without the need to share any images.\r\n\r\nThis is a letter from Draft, written by Nick Disabato. If you want to share it with others, here’s a permalink.\r\n\r\nDon’t want to hear from me anymore? No hard feelings. Unsubscribe.\r\n\r\npo box 47482, Chicago IL 60647	f	2017-09-12 00:30:00	2017-09-12 00:31:20.991216	2017-09-12 00:31:20.991216	The Value Based Product Designer	the-value-based-product-designer	\N	\N	This week on Draft Last week’s Revise Weekly lesson was about repeat sales from past customers. This week’s is about a related aspect: referrals from past customers to existing ones. This fortnight’s Draft Analysis will be about shavin