82	From Execution to Strategic Impact  	## The Challenge  \nEvery so often, you’ll work with a designer who delivers high-quality solutions at speed. Their work is polished, holistic, and well-scoped. They move quickly, stay busy, and are highly dependable.  \n\nBut sometimes, that reliability hides a gap. They’re executing flawlessly within the scope they’re given, yet they’re not shaping strategy or influencing beyond their immediate surface. They’re saying “yes” to the work in front of them, rather than helping define what work matters most.  \n\nAs a manager, the responsibility isn’t just to reward that productivity—it’s to help them grow into someone who can have broader impact.  \n\n## What I Did  \nWhen I encountered this situation, I focused on three actions:  \n\n### 1. Make the Gap Visible  \nI had candid conversations to help the designer see the difference between being an executor and being a strategic leader. We talked openly about where scope was coming from, how strategy was being set, and why they felt pressure to only execute quickly.  \n\n### 2. Create New Lenses  \nTo expand their perspective, I introduced frameworks and exercises:  \n\n- Mapping the system around their surface to see upstream inputs, downstream dependencies, and where value actually flowed.  \n- Using Opportunity Solution Trees to connect problems, opportunities, and solutions in a way that revealed new directions.  \n\nThese tools helped them see beyond the work immediately in front of them and begin identifying opportunities others weren’t yet raising.  \n\n### 3. Encourage Collaborative Framing  \nI coached them to take these insights back to their PM partner—not as pitches, but as collaborative proposals. The shift was subtle but powerful: they weren’t just executing what they were given, they were shaping the agenda together.  \n\n## The Outcome  \nOver time, the designer began to bring forward new opportunities their PM partner embraced. Their relationship shifted from directive to collaborative. Portions of their portfolio were restructured to give them space for vision and framing work alongside execution.  \n\nThe result wasn’t just better design—it was a more strategic partner who could both deliver polished solutions and shape the problems being solved.  \n\n> “The real growth came when they stopped saying ‘yes’ to scope and started helping define it.”  \n\n## Takeaways for Managers  \nIf you’re looking to help a high-performing but execution-heavy designer grow, here are some practical steps:  \n\n1. **Name the gap** — Don’t let productivity mask missed opportunities.  \n2. **Give new lenses** — Frameworks and system-mapping exercises expand their view.  \n3. **Model collaboration** — Encourage them to bring strategic ideas back to partners, not just deliverables.  \n\nIt’s in those moments of reframing and feedback that designers evolve from order-takers into true strategic leaders.  	t	2025-09-05 00:00:00	2025-09-05 17:27:05.633127	2025-09-05 17:27:41.691177	How I helped a designer grow from order-taker to strategic partner by making the gap visible, introducing new frameworks, and encouraging collaboration.	from-execution-to-strategic-impact		\N	The Challenge Every so often, you’ll work with a designer who delivers high-quality solutions at speed. Their work is polished, holistic, and well-scoped. They move quickly, stay busy, and are highly dependable. But sometimes, that reliability hides a gap. They’re executing flawlessly within the scope they’re given, yet they’re not shaping strategy or influencing beyond their immediate surface. They’re saying “yes” to the work in front of them, rather than helping define what work matters most. As a manager, the responsibility isn’t just to reward that productivity—it’s to help them grow into someone who can have broader impact. What I Did When I encountered this situation, I focused on three actions: Make the Gap Visible I had candid conversations to help the designer see the differ