7	Designing For Flow	One of my favorite concepts is flow. Flow is a state in which you are working, and nothing else matters. It's that span of time that felt like 5 minutes, but could have been 50.\r\n\r\nMihály Csíkszentmihályi wrote a book about it in the 90's - it's full of great studies, findings and insights about the attributes of activity that put people into flow. Even better, it suggests the flow might equal happiness. \r\n\r\nWhen I first encountered flow, around 2011, I was seeking an understanding of how to love ones work. It took me several years, many podcasts, many other books and a second reading of Csíkszentmihályi's book to catch the connection with design and flow. \r\n\r\nIt was obvious now that I look back, but because I was seeking an answer about how I could find flow, I wasn't looking at how I could design situations for other people to be in flow. I create experiences, solutions and interfaces constantly. People interact with my work on a daily basis - can I use flow to improve their lives?\r\n\r\nWhen I first approached designing for flow, I questioned the motivation. Was I going to use flow to improve my app's retention metric so I could prove that the app had value? Or, was I using the principals of flow to create a great and engaging experience for the user to bring them joy. It was important to me that I was transparent - even if just to myself for the moment. I didn't want any hidden agenda.\r\n\r\nAs I worked through the question internally, I came to a relatively simple solution to keep me on the right track when designing. I looked at all of the elements of flow, and asked myself with each one, is this for the user or for the application? \r\n\r\nThe elements of flow:\r\n\r\n* A clear goal\r\n* A concentrated field\r\n* Immediate feedback\r\n* The balance between using your skills and being challenged\r\n* A feeling of control\r\n* Ease of the journey\r\n* An altered perception of time\r\n\r\nWhen I design a solution for a person's problem, I try my best to empathize with them. I want to understand their pain points, and design solutions that help remove those pain points and let them achieve their goals.\r\n\r\nwas I helping them transparently achieve their goal, or was I putting them on a path that lead them to achieving my goal, not theirs. As a good designer, this should come natural\r\n\r\n\r\n[Flow](http://www.goodreads.com/book/show/66354.Flow)\r\n[The 8 Elements of Flow](http://www.flowskills.com/the-8-elements-of-flow.html)\r\n\r\n[Flow White Paper](https://web.cs.wpi.edu/~gogo/courses/imgd5100/papers/FlowQuestionnaire.pdf]	f	2017-03-27 02:05:00	2017-03-27 02:05:39.948296	2017-04-02 15:19:32.736261		designing-for-flow	\N	\N	One of my favorite concepts is flow. Flow is a state in which you are working, and nothing else matters. It's that span of time that felt like 5 minutes, but could have been 50. Mihály Csíkszentmihályi wrote a book about it in the 90's - it's full of great studies, findings and insights about the attributes of activity that put people into flow. Even better, it suggests the flow might equal happiness. When I first encountered flow, around 2011, I was seeking an understanding of how to love ones work. It took me several years, many podcasts, many other books and a second reading of Csíkszentmihályi's book to catch the connection with design and flow. It was obvious now that I look back, but because I was seeking an answer about how I could find flow, I wasn't looking at how I could design situations for other people to be in flow. I create experiences, solutions and interfaces constantly. People interact with my work on a daily basis - can I use flow to improve their lives? When I first approached designing for flow, I questioned the motivation. Was I going to use flow to improve my app's retention metric so I could prove that the app had value? Or, was I using the principals of flow to create a great and engaging experience for the user to bring them joy. It was important to me that I was transparent - even if just to myself for the moment. I didn't want any hidden agenda. As I worked through the question internally, I came to a relatively simple solution to keep me on the right track when designing. I looked at all of the elements of flow, and asked myself with each one, is this for the user or for the application? The elements of flow: A clear goal A concentrated field Immediate feedback The balance between using your skills and being challenged A feeling of control Ease of the journey An altered perception of time When I design a solution for a person's problem, I try my best to empathize with them. I want to understand their pain points, and design solutions that help remove those pain points and let them achieve their goals. was I helping them transparently achieve their goal, or was I putting them on a path that lead them to achieving my goal, not theirs. As a good designer, this should come natural Flow The 8 Elements of Flow [Flow White Paper](https://web.cs.wpi.edu/~gogo/courses/imgd5100/papers/FlowQuestionnaire.pdf]
11	Flow & Design Elements	Simply put, "flow" is a highly focused mental state.  It is a level of engagement so concentrated, you don't realize that time has passed until you are out of your flow state. Mikhaly Csikszentmihalyi, the psychologist who coined the term, writes about "flow" in his book _Flow_ - first published in 1990. \r\n\r\nCsikszentmihalyi outlines the qualifications a flow state, and the conditions needed to create one. While I was reading it, it dawned on me how many conditions of flow are baked-in to good design. I am writing a more in depth post about designing for flow, but in the meantime, this post lists the qualifications and conditions of flow to consider when designing.\r\n\r\n## Qualifications\r\n\r\nTo experience flow, means you experience:\r\n\r\n*  Intense and focused concentration on the present moment\r\n* Merging of action and awareness\r\n* A loss of reflective self-consciousness\r\n* A sense of personal control or agency over the situation or activity\r\n* A distortion of temporal experience, one's subjective experience of time is altered\r\n* The activity as intrinsically rewarding\r\n\r\n## Conditions\r\n\r\nTo create a flow state, we want to look at the conditions of flow:\r\n\r\n* High perceived challenges\r\n* High perceived skills\r\n* Knowing what to do\r\n* Knowing how to do it\r\n* Knowing how well you are doing\r\n* Knowing where to go (where navigation is involved)\r\n* Freedom from distractions\r\n\r\n## Checklist\r\n\r\nOwen Schaffer, a user researcher and so much more, came up with a questionnaire we can use to understand if the person using our application is in a flow state:\r\n\r\n#### How much of the time did you know?\r\n\r\n|  | Never | Half the time | Always |\r\n|-|-|-|-|\r\n| What to do next |&#9675;|&#9675;|&#9675;|\r\n| How to do what you were doing |&#9675;|&#9675;|&#9675;|\r\n| How well you were doing |&#9675;|&#9675;|&#9675;|\r\n| Where to go next |&#9675;|&#9675;|&#9675;|\r\n\r\n#### How much did you feel?\r\n\r\n|  | Not at all | Somewhat | Very much |\r\n|-|-|-|-|\r\n| How challenging did this activity feel |&#9675;|&#9675;|&#9675;|\r\n| You could overcome the challenges you faced |&#9675;|&#9675;|&#9675;|\r\n| You were distracted from what you were doing |&#9675;|&#9675;|&#9675;|\r\n\r\n#### Scoring\r\n\r\nReverse the score of the last question to get Freedom from Distractions. The items above are in the following order: Clear What to Do, Clear How to Do it, Clear How Well Doing, Clear Where to Go, Challenge, Skill, and Freedom from Distractions.\r\n\r\n## Moving On\r\n\r\nThe next time you are thinking about designing a user experience, try to think about the qualifications and conditions of flow. \r\n\r\nEnjoy!\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n### References:\r\n\r\n- [Flow](https://www.amazon.com/Flow-Psychology-Experience-Perennial-Classics/dp/0061339202/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&qid=1491137281&sr=8-1&keywords=flow)\r\n- [Crafting Fun Experiences: A Method to Facilitate Flow](https://web.cs.wpi.edu/~gogo/courses/imgd5100/papers/FlowQuestionnaire.pdf)\r\n- [Flow Questionnaire](https://web.cs.wpi.edu/~gogo/courses/imgd5100/papers/FlowQuestionnaire.pdf#19)\r\n- [The 8 Elements of Flow](http://www.flowskills.com/the-8-elements-of-flow.html)\r\n	t	2017-03-03 12:05:00	2017-03-30 12:07:25.6976	2023-05-31 17:32:34.706013		flow-design-elements		\N	Simply put, "flow" is a highly focused mental state. It is a level of engagement so concentrated, you don't realize that time has passed until you are out of your flow state. Mikhaly Csikszentmihalyi, the psychologist who coined the term, writes about "flow" in his book _Flow_ - first published in 1990. Csikszentmihalyi outlines the qualifications a flow state, and the conditions needed to create one. While I was reading it, it dawned on me how many conditions of flow are baked-in to good design. I am writing a more in depth post about designing for flow, but in the meantime, this post lists the qualifications and conditions of flow to consider 