22	What the hell is an MPV?	Working as a consultant, I am always pushing for an MVP. Why? Because they are less expensive to build, and frankly, most poeople don't know what to build. And they shouldn't. Not until a bunch of people are using it, and they can communicate the value of the product. So, let's chat about an MVP - a minimum viable product. \r\n\r\nAn MVP should be 3 things:\r\n\r\n* the least amount of features needed to get the job done\r\n* a journey that is achievable without so much frustration, people quit\r\n* something that adds value\r\n\r\nLet's use IKEA furniture as an example. If I you needed a bed to sleep on and I shipped you a MALBA bed with no instructions, could you build it and have a nice comfy bed to sleep on? Yeah, but with a lot of anguish. It satisfies points one and three, but not two. If people give up because it's so hard, I wouldn't call it an MVP, I'd call it an MP.\r\n\r\nIf we take it a step further and throw some instructions in there, then we've got something. The journey isn't perfect, but it can be accomplished without expending a ton of energy trying to figure it out.\r\n\r\nOne simple way to determine if your product is an MPV is to run a usability test with it. Give your users some goals, and watch them play with it. If they say "I don't know what to do now", and they can't figure it out while spending a reasonable amount of energy, you've got a problem.\r\n\r\nMVPs should be _good enough_ so a user can accomplish their goals without wanting to quit and they should know what to do at each screen to get value out of it.\r\n\r\nNext time you are building an MVP, don't think about how awesome it is, think about how clear it is, and how smooth it is for a user to accomplish their immediate goal. 	f	2017-12-07 02:35:00	2017-12-07 02:45:30.978681	2017-12-07 02:45:30.978681		what-the-hell-is-an-mpv	\N	\N	Working as a consultant, I am always pushing for an MVP. Why? Because they are less expensive to build, and frankly, most po