24	Designing for AI: Input, Output, and Reward 	There are three parts of interaction with AI that we, as product designers, should be designing for: **the input, the output, and the reward**.  \n\n- **The input** — the information a user sends to the machine.  \n- **The output** — the response from the machine to the user.  \n- **The reward** — the follow-up signal the user gives in response to the output.  \n\n### Overt vs. Hidden Signals  \nEach of these—input, output, reward—can be **overt** or **hidden**.  \n\n- **Overt** inputs and rewards are when the user knows they are feeding the machine to get an output. For example: typing a question into a search bar (input), or giving a thumbs up to a generated response (reward).  \n- **Hidden** inputs and rewards are signals the machine picks up without explicit user action—click-through rates, hover behavior, time spent reading, or whether the user abandons a task.  \n\nBoth overt and hidden signals are valuable, but they need to be used with care. Overt signals allow users to feel in control and build trust. Hidden signals can unlock richer context but risk eroding trust if they’re opaque or unexpected.  \n\n### Why It Matters  \nUltimately, the use case determines how we design the interactions: how we structure inputs, how outputs are delivered, and how rewards are collected and used. Getting this wrong risks creating experiences that feel unhelpful, creepy, or frustrating. Getting it right creates experiences that feel natural, useful, and even joyful.  \n\n### Example: ChatGPT’s Chat Design  \nTake ChatGPT’s chat interface. At first glance, it looks almost minimal. But if you consider the framework of input–output–reward, the design fits the use case perfectly.  \n\n- **The input:** A user types freely into an open text field, with almost no guidance.  \n- **The output:** After sending, they receive a conversational text response.  \n- **The reward:** The user can copy the response, give a thumbs up or down, regenerate the output, reply with a new prompt, or simply leave.  \n\nThe true use case here isn’t just giving people answers—it’s learning how people interact with a conversational AI and training the model. For that purpose, the design is excellent: simple, flexible, and structured to collect both overt (thumbs, follow-ups) and hidden (abandonment, time-to-next-prompt) rewards.  \n\n### Hypothetical Example: Finding a Restaurant  \nNow imagine a different use case: *“find the best restaurant near me.”*  \n\nHow might we design the **input**?  \n\n- A simple text box: *“Find the best restaurant near zip code 10001.”*  \n- A text box with suggestions: guiding users on how to phrase their query.  \n- A hidden input: automatically including the user’s location in the query.  \n- A preference builder: letting users pick favorite cuisines, combined with a hidden location input.  \n- A richer signal: asking users to upload photos of dishes they loved in the past, with the hidden location appended.  \n\nEach input design changes not just the experience, but the AI’s ability to deliver a meaningful output and the type of rewards users can give in return.  \n\n### The Opportunity  \nDesigning for AI isn’t new in concept—we’ve always been shaping inputs, outputs, and feedback loops. But with today’s language models, we’re dealing with much more powerful systems. That creates new opportunities to design experiences that are **transparent, valuable, and joyful**.  \n\nSo the challenge for us as designers is this: don’t just stop at the interface. Think deeply about **what signals you’re asking for, what signals you’re collecting silently, and how users understand their role in the loop.**  \n\nHave fun designing! 😃	t	2023-05-17 00:00:00	2023-05-17 14:43:28.996089	2025-09-05 17:13:32.81947	A framework for designing AI interactions around inputs, outputs, and rewards—overt and hidden.  \n	designing-for-ai-input-output-and-reward		\N	There are three parts of interaction with AI that 