81	When Strong Opinions Don’t Win  	## Background  \nAt Grow Therapy, intersession engagement became a critical strategic priority. We knew that improving care quality and demonstrating outcomes meant therapy couldn’t stop at the end of the hour-long session. Clients needed structured ways to reflect between appointments, and providers needed visibility into those reflections.  \n\n---\n\n## The Initial Direction  \nThe team’s early idea was small: 12 hours before a session, send clients a prompt asking what they wanted to discuss. Simple lists of topics would be shared with providers.  \n\nIt worked for some, but I pushed us further. What about clients who didn’t know how to reflect, or who froze at open-ended prompts? The reframing led us to bigger, more ambitious directions: guided prompts, continuity nudges, and different input modes.  \n\n---\n\n## Where I Drew My Line  \nOne approach I personally felt strongly about was **voice-based reflection**.  \n\nThrough research, and learnings from other products in the space, I saw evidence that speaking out loud encouraged deeper, more authentic self-reflection than typing. Clients were more likely to open up when they talked, not when they wrote.  \n\nI built a strong case, shared it with the team, and even brought it to leadership. The product group aligned with me. I believed voice reflection was the future.  \n\n---\n\n## Where I Lost  \nWhen we presented to the CTO, the response was clear: **no voice**.  \n\nThe concerns:  \n- Speaking out loud wasn’t practical for many clients.  \n- The paradigm could feel unnatural or uncomfortable.  \n- The company wasn’t ready to take the risk of introducing such a new behavior.  \n\nI disagreed. I felt strongly we were missing an opportunity. But I also knew this wasn’t a battle to keep fighting.  \n\n---\n\n## Conceding, and Moving Forward  \nInstead of holding onto my opinion, I conceded. I committed to the decision, realigned the team, and focused on building the **best possible text-based reflection experience**.  \n\nThat meant designing for open reflections, summarizing them with AI into clear topics, and creating a smarter prompting system that was contextual rather than one-size-fits-all.  \n\n---\n\n## The Outcome  \nSession Topics shipped successfully:  \n- Clients reflected at high rates.  \n- Providers received clear, structured prep material.  \n- The initiative proved that intersession engagement could drive care quality and support payor outcomes.  \n\nMy belief in voice reflection didn’t disappear—but I learned that **being right isn’t the same as being effective**.  \n\n---\n\n## Reflection  \nThis story is less about the feature itself and more about leadership.  \n\n- **Strong beliefs**: I did the work, had conviction, and advocated for my opinion.  \n- **Weakly held**: When leadership decided differently, I didn’t cling to it.  \n- **Concession**: I embraced the decision, drove alignment, and kept the team moving.  \n\nIn the end, the team shipped a feature that was clear and reinforced intersession engagement for both the client and provider. And I came away with a deeper understanding: as a leader, sometimes the most impactful thing you can do is to **let go of being right, and commit to being aligned**.  	t	2025-09-01 00:00:00	2025-09-05 17:07:22.797252	2025-09-05 17:09:37.69231	How I learned to concede gracefully on Session Topics—even when I believed I was right.	when-strong-opinions-don-t-win		\N	Background At Grow Therapy, intersession engagement became a critical strategic priority. We knew that improving care quality and demonstrating outcomes meant therapy couldn’t stop at the end of the hour-long session. Clients needed structured ways to reflect between appointments, and providers needed visibility into those reflections. --- The Initial Direction The team’s early idea was small: 12 hours before a session, send clients a prompt asking what they wanted to discuss. Simple lists of topics would be shared wi