83	Creating Space for New Talent to Shine	## The Situation  \nDuring 2022 planning, we gained a second researcher in our area—a senior IC with deep domain knowledge. (I’ll call her **“Maria”** here, though that’s not her real name.)  \n\nAs the design lead, my immediate responsibility was to integrate her smoothly into the team. But my longer-term goal was bigger: I wanted research to play a stronger role in our strategy.  \n\n## The Actions I Took  \n\n### Start With Understanding  \nI began with regular 1:1s to learn about Maria’s role, her aspirations, and what motivated her. These conversations started casually but quickly moved toward the work. She was particularly drawn to **generative research**, and I wanted to create space for that.  \n\n### Expand Strategic Involvement  \nI broadened our strategy meetings to include her voice, adjusted priorities so her work had impact, and made sure her research agenda was integrated into action. One of her early projects—a study we’ll call “Team Types”—was a breakthrough. It positioned her as a domain expert and gave our team valuable new insights.  \n\n### Create Visibility and Evangelize  \nI didn’t want her research to sit in a doc somewhere. I actively created opportunities for her work to be shared: in team meetings, across our area, and upwards into leadership conversations. This both amplified her impact and showed the team how powerful embedded research could be.  \n\n### Support Growth Beyond IC Work  \nMaria told me she was interested in management. Alongside integrating her work, I made time to mentor her on leadership, helping her prepare for that next step.  \n\n## The Outcome  \nThe results were twofold:  \n\n- **For the team:** Maria’s research shaped strategy in meaningful ways, increasing the role of research in how we made decisions.  \n- **For her career:** She grew her scope, gained visibility, and eventually transitioned into management.  \n\nWhat made the difference wasn’t just creating space for her to contribute—it was making sure that contribution was visible, impactful, and tied to her motivations.  \n\n> “The opportunity for her to shine wasn’t accidental. It was built into the process.”  \n\n## Key Lessons for Leaders  \n- Start with understanding: learn what motivates new senior hires.  \n- Expand strategy meetings to include their voice early.  \n- Evangelize their work so it creates visible impact.  \n- Connect opportunities to their aspirations for long-term growth.  \n\nWhen you intentionally design the space for new talent to shine, you elevate both the individual and the team.  	t	2024-03-21 00:00:00	2025-09-05 17:27:56.644759	2025-09-05 17:31:42.778744	How I integrated a new senior researcher into strategy, created space for her to shine, and supported her path to leadership.\n	creating-space-for-new-talent-to-shine		\N	The Situation During 2022 planning, we gained a second researcher in our area—a senior IC with deep domain knowledge. (I’ll call her “Maria” here, though that’s not her real name.) As the design lead, my immediate responsibility was to integrate her smoothly into the team. But my longer-term goal was bigger: I wanted research to play a stronger role in our strategy. The Actions I Took Start With Understanding I began with regular 1:1s to learn about Maria’s role, her aspirations, and what motivated her. These conversations started casually but quickly moved toward the work. She was particularly drawn to generative research, and I wanted to create space for that. Expand Strategic Involvement I broadened our strategy meetings to include her voice, adjusted priorities so her work had impact, and made sure her research agenda was integrated into action. One of her early projects—a study we’ll call “Team Types”—was a breakthrough. It positioned her as a domain expert and gave our team valuable new insights. Create Visibility and Evangelize I didn’t want her research to sit in a doc somewhere. I actively created opportunities for her wo