84	Building Trust With a New Partner Through Innovation 	## The Situation  \nIn Q3 of 2019, reorganization and attrition reshaped my group. My area was combined with others, and I gained a new product lead and partner. (I’ll call her **“Taylor”** here, though that’s not her real name.)  \n\nTaylor was an experienced leader with a reputation for strong execution. I had never worked with her before, and our first challenge was clear: set expectations, build trust, and establish a strong working relationship.  \n\n## The Actions I Took  \n\n### Collaborative Expectation-Setting  \nBecause we were new to each other, I proposed that we co-create our working agreement. We wrote out our responsibilities together, then aligned individually to find gaps. This gave us clarity and set a tone of shared ownership.  \n\n### Apply the Framework: Understand, Achieve, Grow  \nFrom there, I followed my usual process:  \n\n1. **Understand** — Learn each other’s motivators.  \n2. **Achieve** — Find a project to deliver success together.  \n3. **Grow** — Support each other’s development.  \n\nIn our early conversations, I learned Taylor had a strong interest in **innovation** and taking greater risks.  \n\n### Finding the First Win  \nIn our first strategy-setting session, I raised the topic of innovation. Coming from a design background with a lot of 0→1 experience, I shared tools like Design Sprints and Forum Traversing. Taylor asked me to lead on testing innovation processes, and I suggested we collaborate instead. Together, we adapted the GV Design Sprint to fit our needs.  \n\nTwo teams tested the variation, and the outcomes were actionable and energizing. Taylor was thrilled and eager to expand the effort.  \n\n### Codifying Innovation Practice  \nBuilding on that success, I worked with Taylor to add more design exercises—ritual descent, analogous inspiration, and others. We piloted an “innovation week,” dedicating a week each quarter to forward-looking projects. The process was later codified across our area, creating space for risk-taking and experimentation alongside execution.  \n\n## The Outcome  \nInnovation week produced product changes and morale boosts. More importantly, it built trust between Taylor and me. We had taken a vague goal—“let’s work well together”—and turned it into a process that delivered both outcomes and partnership.  \n\n> “Getting a win together through innovation created momentum that carried into everything else we did.”  \n\n## Key Lessons  \n- Co-create expectations with new partners to set the right tone.  \n- Learn motivators early; they unlock opportunities for collaboration.  \n- Find an early win together—it builds momentum and trust.  \n- Codify successful practices so they scale beyond the initial experiment.  \n\n---\n\n**TL;DR (Audio-Ready Script)**  \n\n> \n\n**Navigate-To Button TL;DR**  \nH	t	2023-10-20 00:00:00	2025-09-05 17:36:00.357672	2025-09-05 17:36:56.876331	How I built trust with a new product partner by co-creating expectations and delivering an early win through innovation. 	building-trust-with-a-new-partner-through-innovation		\N	The Situation In Q3 of 2019, reorganization and attrition reshaped my group. My area was combined with others, and I gained a new product lead and partner. (I’ll call her “Taylor” here, though that’s not her real name.) Taylor was an experienced leader with a reputation for strong execution. I had never worked with her before, and our first challenge was clear: set expectations, build trust, and establish a strong working relationship. The Actions I Took Collaborative Expectation-Setting Because we were new to each other, I proposed that we co-create our working agreement. We wrote out our responsibilities together, then aligned individually to find gaps. This gave us clarity and set a tone of shared ownership. Apply the Framework: Understand, Achieve, Grow From there, I followed my usual process: Understand — Learn each other’s motivators. Achieve — Find a proj